{{Infobox language |name=Baram |nativename=Baraamu |region=[[Nepal]] |ethnicity={{sigfig|7,380|2}} (2001 census)<ref name=e18/> |speakers=160 |date=2011 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Newaric languages|Newaric]] |fam3=[[Baram–Thangmi languages|Baram–Thangmi]] |iso3=brd |glotto=bara1357 |glottorefname=Baraamu }}
'''Baram''' (Baraamu, Bhramu) is a small [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan language]] spoken in Nepal. Speakers are shifting to [[Nepali language|Nepali]]. Dialects are Dandagaun and Mailung.
==Locations== Baram is spoken in [[Dandagaun, Gorkha|Dandagaun]]<!--None of the entries on the DAB page is in the named district or zone--> and [[Mailung]] VDCs in central and southern [[Gorkha District]], [[Gandaki Zone]], and in Takhu village up the Doraundi Khola (east side above Chorgate, near Kumhali) (''Ethnologue''). There are possibly about 7 villages in [[Dhading District]].
